{{For|the Brazilian composer|Oscar Lorenzo Fernández}} {{Use mdy dates|date=August 2013}} {{Infobox football biography | name = Lorenzo Fernández | image = | caption = The Uruguay squad posing before the end of 1930. Fernandez is the fourth player standing from left to right | fullname = | birth_date = {{birth date|1900|05|20}} | birth_place = [[Redondela]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.farodevigo.es/deportes/2653/lorenzo-fdez-redondelano-uruguay/68443.html|title=Lorenzo Fdez. Un redondelano en Uruguay|trans_title= Lorenzo Fdez. A redondelan in Uruguay|publisher=[[Faro de Vigo]]|date=June 8, 2006|language=Spanish}}</ref> Spain | death_date = {{Death date and age|1973|11|16|1900|05|20}} | death_place = [[Montevideo]], Uruguay | height = | position = [[Formation (association football)#2–3–5 (Pyramid)|halfback]] (center-half) | youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = | years1 = 1915–1917 | clubs1 = C.A. Capurro | caps1 = | goals1 = | years2 = 1918 | clubs2 = [[River Plate Football Club|River Plate F.C.]] | caps2 = | goals2 = | years3 = 1919–1922 | clubs3 = C.A. Capurro | caps3 = | goals3 = | years4 = 1923 | clubs4 = [[Montevideo Wanderers|Atlético Wanderers]] | caps4 = | goals4 = | years5 = 1924–1928 | clubs5 = C.A. Capurro | caps5 = | goals5 = | years6 = 1928–1935 | clubs6 = [[C.A. Peñarol|Peñarol]] | caps6 = | goals6 = | totalcaps = | totalgoals = | nationalyears1 = 1925–1935 | nationalteam1 = [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]] | nationalcaps1 = 31 | nationalgoals1 = 4 | manageryears1 = 1941–1942 | managerclubs1 = [[C.A. Peñarol|Peñarol]] | manageryears2 = 1950 | managerclubs2 = [[Liverpool F.C. (Montevideo)|Liverpool]] | medaltemplates = {{MedalCountry|{{URU}}}} {{MedalSport | Men's [[Football at the Summer Olympics|football]]}} {{MedalGold | [[1928 Summer Olympics|1928 Amsterdam]] | [[Football at the 1928 Summer Olympics|Team Competition]]}} }} {{MedalTop}} {{MedalCountry|{{URU}}}} {{MedalSport | Men's [[Football at the Summer Olympics|Football]]}} {{MedalGold | [[1928 Summer Olympics|1928 Amsterdam]] | [[Football at the 1928 Summer Olympics|Team Competition]]}} {{MedalBottom}}
'''Lorenzo Fernández''' (May 20, 1900 – November 16, 1973), nicknamed ''El Gallego'' (The [[Galician people|Galician]]), was a Spanish-born Uruguayan [[Association football|footballer]]. During his career, he played for Capurro, River Plate, [[Montevideo Wanderers FC]] and [[C.A. Peñarol]]. Fernández also played 31 times and scored 4 goals for the [[Uruguay national football team]], with which he won the [[1930 FIFA World Cup]], the gold medal at the [[1928 Summer Olympics]], and the 1926 and 1935 Copa Americas. A [[Formation (association football)#2–3–5 (Pyramid)|center-half]] in the 2–3–5 footballing system, he once replaced [[Pedro Cea|Jose Pedro Cea]] as an [[Formation (association football)#2–3–5 (Pyramid)|inside-left]] forward against [[Peru national football team|Peru]] for the [[1929 South American Championship]] (the then [[Copa América|Copa America]]) and scored a [[hat-trick|hat trick]].
In 1941 and 1942, he coached [[C.A. Peñarol|Peñarol]].<ref>http://girasolweb.tripod.com/tecnicos.htm</ref>
