{{Infobox football biography |name= Ernesto Mascheroni |image= |caption = The Uruguay squad posing before the end of 1930. Mascheroni is the first player standing, from left |fullname= Ernesto Mascheroni |birth_date= {{birth date|df=yes|1907|11|21}} | birth_place = [[Montevideo]], [[Uruguay]] |death_date= 3 July 1984 (age 76) | death_place = [[Montevideo]], [[Uruguay]] |height= {{convert|1.85|m|ftin|0|abbr=on}} |position= [[Left back]] | years1 = 1920s-1932 | clubs1 = [[Club Atlético River Plate (Montevideo)|Olimpia]] | caps1 = | goals1 = | years2 = 1932-1934 | clubs2 = [[Club Atlético River Plate (Montevideo)|River Plate (Uruguay)]] | caps2 = | goals2 = | years3 = 1934-1936 | clubs3 = [[F.C. Internazionale Milano|Ambrosiana]] | caps3 = | goals3 = | years4 = 1936-1940 | clubs4 = [[C.A. Peñarol|Peñarol]] | caps4 = | goals4 = | totalcaps = | totalgoals = | nationalyears1 = 1930-1939 | nationalteam1 = [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]] | nationalcaps1 = 12 | nationalgoals1 = | nationalyears2 = 1935-1936 | nationalteam2 = [[Italy national football team|Italy]] | nationalcaps2 = 2 | nationalgoals2 = | medaltemplates = }}
'''Ernesto Mascheroni''' (21 November 1907 – 3 July 1984) was a [[football (soccer)|footballer]] from [[Uruguay]]. Born in Montevideo, Ernesto was a [[defender (football)|defender]]. He played as a [[left-back]].
He played 12 times for the [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]] between 1930 and 1939, including in the [[1930 FIFA World Cup]] where Uruguay won the first ever World Cup tournament. In 1934, he moved to [[Italy]] to play for [[F.C. Internazionale Milano|Ambrosiana]] (now Inter Milan) until 1936. During this period, he represented the [[Italy national football team]] twice, when the nationality rules were less strict than they now are. He later returned to Uruguay to play for [[C.A. Peñarol]] from 1936 to 1940.
By the time of his death in July 1984, at the age of 76, he was the last surviving member of Uruguay's 1930 World Cup winning team; though it would be another 26 years before the death of the [[Francisco Varallo|last surviving participant of that World Cup]].<ref>"[http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-11134965 Last surviving player from first World Cup final dies]." BBC News, 31 Aug. 2010. 22 March 2011.</ref>
