{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2011}} {{Expand German|date=February 2009|Étienne Mattler}} {{Infobox football biography | name= Étienne Mattler | image = | fullname = Étienne Mattler | height = {{convert|1.91|m|ftin|0|abbr=on}} | birth_date = 25 December 1905 | birth_place = [[Belfort]], France | death_date = 23 March 1986 (age 80) | death_place = [[Sochaux]], France | position = [[Fullback (association football)|Full back]] | youthyears1= | youthclubs1= | years1 = 1921–1927 | years2 = 1927–1929 | years3 =1929–1946 | clubs1 = [[US Belfort]] | clubs2 = [[Troyes AC|Troyes]] | clubs3 = [[FC Sochaux-Montbéliard|Sochaux]] | caps1 = 214 | goals1 = 10 | caps2 = 142 | goals2 = 4 | caps3 = 125 | goals3 = 2 | nationalyears1 = 1930–40 | nationalteam1 = [[France national football team|France]] | nationalcaps1 = 46 | nationalgoals1 = 0 | manageryears1 = 1944–46 | managerclubs1 = [[FC Sochaux-Montbéliard|Sochaux]]<ref>[http://www.rsssf.com/players/trainers-fran-clubs.html France – Trainers of First and Second Division Clubs<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> }} '''Étienne Mattler''' (25 December 1905 – 23 March 1986) was a [[List of France international footballers|French international footballer]], nicknamed ''Le Lion de Belfort''.
Mattler, born in [[Belfort]], played for the clubs US Belfort (1921–1927), [[Troyes AC]] (1927–1929), and [[FC Sochaux-Montbéliard|FC Sochaux]] (1929–1946) where he won two [[Ligue 1]] titles in 1935 and 1938 and one [[Coupe de France]] in 1937.
For the national team, he won 46 [[cap (sport)|caps]] and participated in the [[1930 FIFA World Cup|1930]], [[1934 FIFA World Cup|1934]] and [[1938 FIFA World Cup|1938]] [[FIFA World Cup|World Cups]], being one of five players to have appeared in all three of the pre-war World Cups.<ref>The other players were [[Edmond Delfour]], [[Nicolae Kovács]], [[Bernard Voorhoof]] and [[Rodolpho Barteczko|Patesko]], according to official [[FIFA]] match reports. Patesko, however, is not listed in many sources as part of the 1930 Brazilian squad, shortening the list to four players.</ref> He died at 80 years old.
